article.headline: Northern Iowa 70, Iowa State 57
article.story: CEDAR FALLS, Iowa (AP) -- Northern Iowa's winning formula was simple. The Panthers controlled the glass, protected the basketball and made the right plays at the right time. Ironically, that's a strategy they learned playing for the coach on the losing team. Brooks McKowen scored a career-high 27 points and Eric Coleman added 17 points and 11 rebounds to lead Northern Iowa past Iowa State 70-57 Wednesday, spoiling former coach Greg McDermott's return to Cedar Falls. Travis Brown chipped in with 16 and Grant Stout had 10 boards for the Panthers (5-1), who beat Iowa State (6-1) for the second time in eight tries. "I think at the end of all of it our experience probably won out," Northern Iowa coach Ben Jacobson said. "Brooks, Eric and Grant all had pretty good games. ... They made the plays tonight to give us the win." Both McDermott and Jacobson formerly coached at North Dakota State and the University of North Dakota. McDermott, who jumped to Iowa State last spring after five seasons at Northern Iowa, knew the Panthers would pose the biggest challenge his young team had seen all season. He was right. Northern Iowa outrebounded the Cyclones, committed fewer turnovers and made 17 free throws to just five for Iowa State. "Tonight was the first time all year that we played an experienced basketball team that really knows how to play the game," McDermott said. "They really exploited some things that we're not too good at." Down six late in the second half, Iowa State couldn't force a stop defensively and the Panthers capitalized. McKowen buried a pair of free throws, and Brown followed with a 3-pointer that gave Northern Iowa a 60-49 lead with 2:56 left. Jiri Hubalek made it interesting by hitting a 3 with 1:20 left to pull the Cyclones within five. But Coleman made a steal and drove 65 feet for a thunderous dunk, putting an exclamation point on the Panthers' win. "That was the nail in the coffin," Coleman said. Wesley Johnson led Iowa State with 14 points and Rahshon Clark added 12 points and 10 rebounds. Mike Taylor, the Cyclones' leading scorer, scored five points. Iowa State opened the second half with a 13-4 run and tied the game at 37 on a Johnson 3-pointer off the glass. That's as close as the Cyclones got. Northern Iowa maintained a two-possession lead for much of the second half, and pushed it to 55-49 late in the game. "We didn't shoot the ball well," Clark said. "We had chances to come back and take the lead. We just couldn't put the ball in the basket." McKowen and Brown hit consecutive 3s to put the Panthers ahead 26-20, and McKowen buried a 3-pointer with two seconds left in the first half to give Northern Iowa a 33-24 lead at the break. The lead changed hands eight times in the first half. Hubalek, back after serving a six-game suspension for violating NCAA rules, struggled to find his shooting touch in his first outing of the year. Hubalek, a 6-foot-11 center, consistently settled for perimeter jump shots that rattled off the rim. He finished 4-for-18 from the floor in 35 minutes, playing almost the entire way with Ross Marsden out with the flu. "You give Jiri 18 shots, he's not going to make four of them very often," McDermott said. "The guy can really shoot the basketball." McDermott led the Panthers to an unprecedented three straight NCAA tournament trips and their first-ever Top 25 ranking last season, but he was greeted with lukewarm applause -- at best -- when he was introduced before the game. "I appreciated the hospitality," McDermott said. "I thought the fans were very kind. This place means a lot to me, and it always will." Northern Iowa officials were a bit more excited about McDermott's return. They moved the game to the UNI Dome, which has twice the capacity of the new McLeod Center, and charged $30 a ticket -- twice the normal rate. They also presented McDermott, along with three current Iowa State assistants, with 2006 NCAA Tournament rings before the game. That didn't generate much of a buzz from the crowd, either. They saved most of their cheers for McKowen, who went 3-for-3 from beyond the arc, made 12 of 13 free throws, had seven rebounds and six assists. "I spent three years with Brooks. A lot of people complain about what Brooks can't do. I was never one of them," McDermott said. "Brooks just wins."
